### Insurance Fraud Detection — LIVE DEMO (2 legit + 1 fraud)
###
### Source data : ml/data/fraud_oracle.xlsx → ml/data/fraud_oracle_tathergaenge.csv
### Companion doc: ./live-demo.md  (runbook, talking points, image-generation prompts)
### Monitoring   : ./monitor.http  (OData queries) + the Claims Fiori app
###
### HOW TO RUN
###   1. Start the backend with the open-source track live (OpenRouter):
###        CF_HOME=. OSS_LLM_SOURCE=destination cds watch --profile hybrid
###   2. Fire the requests below in order.
###   3. Open the Claims app → each claim runs the full pipeline autonomously:
###        submitClaim → StructureClaim → PredictFraud (N) → EvaluateClaim (M) → Review
###   4. Open a claim's Object Page → Predictions + Evaluations tables show the
###      side-by-side model comparison; the List Report shows the risk-level columns.
###
### Each case carries a known `actualFraud` label (ground truth from FraudFound_P),
### so the UI colours each model's predicted-vs-actual decision (green = correct).
###
### The `predictModels` / `evaluations` run config can ALSO be set interactively in
### the UI via the "Pipeline Configuration (Advanced)" panel in the Submit dialog.
###
### Models: predict → sap-rpt-1-large (SAP RPT-1, proprietary) + custom ML (gbc/rf,
###         local FastAPI). evaluate → anthropic--claude-4.6-opus (proprietary) and
###         the open-source LLMs gpt-oss-120b / gpt-oss-20b / gemma-3-27b (OpenRouter).

@intakeUrl = http://localhost:4004/api/intake


### ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
### CASE A — LEGITIMATE, well documented  (actualFraud = false)   [warm-up]
### Presentation summary: A tidy, well-documented Honda claim establishes the
### baseline where both proprietary and open-source tracks should agree it is legit.
### ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

POST {{intakeUrl}}/submitClaim
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "externalRef": "DEMO-A-LEGIT-CLEAN",
  "rawText": "I had a single-vehicle accident on a Wednesday in mid-January. Coming back through the city late at night in my Honda Sport - the high-trim version - I hit ice on an off-ramp and clipped the concrete barrier. The front quarter panel, headlight, and bumper assembly all took the hit. I called the police given the location and they filed a report, even though no one else was involved. I'm in my mid-thirties, this is my first claim on this policy, and I'm covering the $400 deductible.",
  "predictModels": ["sap-rpt-1-large", "gbc"],
  "evaluations": [
    { "model": "anthropic--claude-4.6-opus", "inputPredictModel": "sap-rpt-1-large" },
    { "model": "gpt-oss-120b",               "inputPredictModel": "gbc" }
  ],
  "actualFraud": false
}

###


### ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
### CASE B — LEGITIMATE but looks fraudy: false-positive trap  (actualFraud = false)
### Presentation summary: This honest Ford claim looks suspicious on paper, making
### it the false-positive trap that tests whether the models stay calibrated.
### ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

POST {{intakeUrl}}/submitClaim
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "externalRef": "DEMO-B-LEGIT-LOOKSFRAUDY",
  "rawText": "In mid-April I sideswiped a parked van on a narrow city street with my Ford Utility - it's an older expensive vehicle but big and solid. The damage to the passenger side runs along the door and rear panel, and the wing mirror was knocked clean off. The van's owner wasn't there so I left a note and waited; he called within an hour and we sorted it. The body shop has been finding more things to fix as they go, so supplements have been adding up. I've had a few claims over the years - work driving wear and tear. Deductible $400.",
  "predictModels": ["sap-rpt-1-large", "gbc"],
  "evaluations": [
    { "model": "anthropic--claude-4.6-opus", "inputPredictModel": "sap-rpt-1-large" },
    { "model": "gpt-oss-120b",               "inputPredictModel": "gbc" }
  ],
  "actualFraud": false
}

###


### ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
### CASE C — CLEAR FRAUD, maximum red flags  (actualFraud = true)   [headline]
### Presentation summary: The Chevrolet claim stacks multiple red flags and should
### be the clear fraud case where both tracks raise the alarm.
### ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

POST {{intakeUrl}}/submitClaim
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "externalRef": "DEMO-C-FRAUD-REDFLAGS",
  "rawText": "On a Tuesday in mid-November I had a single-vehicle accident on a busy urban road - drifted and clipped a concrete divider. My Chevrolet Utility is a high-end model, seven years old. Front-driver corner took the brunt, plus underbody work. The body shop has been adding pieces over the months and supplements keep coming through as they uncover more. I've been with this insurer for years, hardly ever had to file before - just the odd small thing here and there - so the paperwork has taken a while to settle. Wrapped up in January. I'm in my early thirties, married. $400 deductible.",
  "predictModels": ["sap-rpt-1-large", "gbc"],
  "evaluations": [
    { "model": "anthropic--claude-4.6-opus", "inputPredictModel": "sap-rpt-1-large" },
    { "model": "gpt-oss-120b",               "inputPredictModel": "gbc" }
  ],
  "actualFraud": true
}

